<article>
    <h1>Heng visits Brunei to of&#xAD;fer con&#xAD;do&#xAD;lences on death of Sul&#xAD;tan&#x2019;s son</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201111/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-11"><time>2020-11-11</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline">Char&#xAD;maine Ng ngxtc@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Deputy Prime Min­is­ter Heng Swee Keat vis­ited Brunei yes­ter­day to of­fer his con­do­lences on be­half of the Sin­ga­pore Gov­ern­ment to Brunei’s Sul­tan Has­sanal Bolkiah on the death of his son, Prince ‘Ab­dul ‘Azim.</p>
    <p>Mr Heng, who is also Co­or­di­nat­ing Min­is­ter for Eco­nomic Poli­cies and Min­is­ter for Fi­nance, had an au­di­ence with the Sul­tan.</p>
    <p>He also called on and was hosted to lunch by Crown Prince Al-Muh­tadee Bil­lah, who is Se­nior Min­is­ter at the Prime Min­is­ter’s Of­fice of Brunei.</p>
    <p>Mr Heng and Crown Prince Bil­lah reaf­firmed the ex­cel­lent state of bi­lat­eral re­la­tions and ex­plored ways to con­tinue deep­en­ing col­lab­o­ra­tion, Sin­ga­pore’s Min­istry of For­eign Af­fairs (MFA) said in a state­ment.</p>
    <p>Ac­com­pa­ny­ing Mr Heng on the trip were Dr Ma­liki Os­man, Min­is­ter in the Prime Min­is­ter’s Of­fice (PMO) and Sec­ond Min­is­ter for Ed­u­ca­tion and For­eign Af­fairs, as well as of­fi­cials from the PMO and MFA.</p>
    <p>“Prince ‘Azim was well known for his ded­i­ca­tion to de­vel­op­ing more op­por­tu­ni­ties for youth, and help­ing the less for­tu­nate in so­ci­ety,” Mr Heng wrote in a Face­book post yes­ter­day.</p>
    <p>“Prince ‘Azim stud­ied in Sin­ga­pore dur­ing his school­ing years and was also a friend of Sin­ga­pore,” he added.</p>
    <p>Prince ‘Ab­dul ‘Azim died of mul­ti­ple or­gan fail­ure on Oct 24 due to an au­toim­mune dis­ease.</p>
    <p>He was 38.</p>
    <p>He was di­ag­nosed with se­vere sys­temic vas­culi­tis ear­lier this year, a con­di­tion char­ac­terised by in­flam­ma­tion of blood ves­sel walls.</p>
    <p>Fourth in line to suc­ceed the throne of Brunei, Prince ‘Ab­dul ‘Azim was the sec­ond son of Sul­tan Has­sanal Bolkiah.</p>
    <p>He stud­ied at the In­ter­na­tional School Brunei, Sin­ga­pore’s Raf­fles In­sti­tu­tion and Ox­ford Brookes Univer­sity.</p>
    <p>Mr Heng said of his meet­ing with Crown Prince Bil­lah: “We agreed to ex­plore new ways to fur­ther deepen col­lab­o­ra­tion be­tween our two coun­tries.”</p>
    <p>He added: “I look for­ward to wel­com­ing His Majesty and HRH Crown Prince Bil­lah to Sin­ga­pore when con­di­tions for in­ter­na­tional travel are more favourable.”</p>

